TextChange: It is no secret that first impressions matter. In advertising, companies know that if their products do not look interesting at first glance, consumers are more likely to overlook them. People tend to be attracted to things that look great on the outside, it is the very first thing they see about a product or even a person. Even in the age of social media and technology, people tend to use the same formula for promoting themselves; sharing the good parts of their lives so that their viewers will have the idea that that person's life is perfect and glamorous. This is a very smart marketing tactic, but in some cases it can definitely have too much of an effect on people.\n

ple use these tactics and sometimes the image that they are trying to portray may be accurate. That product may be high quality and the packaging reflects the effort put into that quality. That person's life may be absolutely perfect. This unfortunately is not always the case. Companies may sometimes try to disguise a low quality product with flashy packaging because they know that not everyone will look deeper into the quality if the product itself looks fantastic at the surface. Politicians may promote their policies to win the votes but their time in office may end up filled with broken promises and disappointments. Celebrities and influencers may hide the bad parts about their lives to give off the image that their lives are glamorous when they are battling their own issues deep down.

oThis can hurt regular people who consume products and media because they may buy into the idea that what they are getting will be good for them but they may be highly disappointed after chasing and obtaining whatever it may be.

Images and impressions are definitely important when it comes to marketing ones product and brand. When done correctly and honestly, it can lead consumers to great products, services, and content. Producers should be honest about what they are marketing so that consumers can make educated decisions on the things that they buy or the media that they consume. It is, however, important for consumers to really look deeper than the surface to avoid committing to a product, service, or lifestyle that may be harmful to them, especially if that information is not readily available to them. People should always be careful and know everything about a brand before making decisions.
